<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-451-529  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 451 529.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Sept 1990 v7 n9 p198(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Understanding fiber optics. (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Botelho, Margot A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A number of factors are combining to spur the growth of fiberoptic cable.andP;  High speed local area networks (LANs), linkedmultiple LANs, high bandwidth requirements, or plans for futureimplementation of Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) or imageprocessing all call for fiber optics.andP;  Advantages of fiber opticsover twisted pair or coaxial cable include immunity toelectromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequencyinterference (RFI), distance capability, small size, andlightweight.andP;  Optical fiber is electrically non-conductive(dielectric), offering not only EMI/RFI immunity, which promotesdata integrity and reduces transmission errors, but also immunityto lightening strikes, safety in hazardous or explosiveenvironments, and ground plane isolation.andP;  Network operatingcharacteristics are a function of the type of optical fiber chosenfor a network.andP;  Key cabling parameters to be specified includebandwidth, attenuation, chromatic dispersion, and fiber geometry.andO;Cable design is determined by the number of fibers, type of fiberprotection, and outer sheathing or jacket.andP;  Selection of a designdepends on installation environment, number of terminations,building code requirements, and whether individual fibers must bebroken out for termination in different places.andP;  Cableinstallation can be as costly as the purchase price of fiber opticcable, and employing outside expertise to help in planning andspecification is a worthwhile investment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialFiber OpticsPlanningCablesSpecifications.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   The core glass of optical fiber is surrounded by the claddingglass. (chart)A major benefit of multimode fiber is that it uses inexpensiveLEDs. (chart)Comparative chromatic dispersion of lasers vs. LEDs. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>